<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="BAL02" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">James</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Ballantyne</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1772-01-15"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1833-01-17"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">printer</occupation><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">newspaper editor</occupation><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Ballantyne was a prominent Scottish printer who is best known for printing much of <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="SCO03">Sir Walter Scott's</persName> work. 
    In 1796 he travelled to 
  London to make business contacts and here he met Godwin, dining at <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="HOL01">Holcroft's</persName>. A letter from Ballantyne to Godwin dated 
    14 November 1799 confirms the identification. Ballantyne wrote the letter to introduce Dr Bell, a physician about to sail to the West Indies. Bell called on Godwin 
    13 December 1799.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">It is thought that references to 'Ballantine' originally refer to James and then to <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="BAL03">John</persName>. Godwin's initial contact is with 
